  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThe article argues that, for team‑based development, squash‑merge is the safer, more collaborative choice over interactive rebasing when creating release tags or cleaning up history. It contrasts the two mental models—rebasing to rewrite history versus merging to combine whole branches—and lists concrete pros and cons (rebasing gives “absolute power” but can cause endless conflict resolution and lose PR comments; squash‑merge is simpler, non‑destructive, and preserves review context). The piece is written as a pragmatic, slightly tongue‑in‑cheek tutorial aimed at engineers who work on shared repositories (open‑source or corporate), using battle‑metaphor language (“deathmatch”, “black belt in git fu”) to frame the debate. The intended audience is developers who need to decide a commit‑strategy that balances individual workflow preferences with team usability.",
